WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.420
So, I'm going to be talking about the MAJESTIC-3 trial, which I think is one of those, I think

00:00:05.420 --> 00:00:10.900
we will in the future regard this as a pretty landmark study.

00:00:10.900 --> 00:00:16.160
So I want to talk about how this has really changed, will change, and has changed my practice

00:00:16.160 --> 00:00:19.040
already.

00:00:19.040 --> 00:00:23.100
So I'll start with my conclusion, which is that, and this may be a little controversial,

00:00:23.100 --> 00:00:29.460
but we should prefer TEK plus or minus daratumumab over CAR-T cells like cilta-cel and second

00:00:29.460 --> 00:00:34.340
line of therapy based on the results of MAJESTIC-3.

00:00:34.340 --> 00:00:41.200
So I think over the last several years of immunotherapy for myeloma, the working assumption

00:00:41.200 --> 00:00:45.720
has been that CAR-T cells are more potent than Bispecific.

00:00:45.720 --> 00:00:52.060
And that was really based on the separate phase 1, 2 studies of cilta-cel and various

00:00:52.060 --> 00:00:56.260
Bispecific like teclistamab, where the cilta-cel response rates were these really

00:00:56.260 --> 00:00:58.920
just unbelievable response rates of 97, 98%.

00:00:58.920 --> 00:01:04.380
And then if you looked at the single-arm studies of various Bispecific like teclistamab,

00:01:04.380 --> 00:01:09.760
the response rates were in the 60 to 70% range.

00:01:09.760 --> 00:01:13.580
Although there were always, I think, some underappreciated caveats to that assumption.

00:01:13.580 --> 00:01:18.980
So first, the top line overall response rate for CAR-T cell studies often doesn't include

00:01:18.980 --> 00:01:20.580
the non-infused patients.

00:01:20.580 --> 00:01:23.720
And the patients who don't get infused are often sicker, they're the patients who fail

00:01:23.720 --> 00:01:27.660
manufacturing because their T cells aren't very healthy, and there was also very likely

00:01:27.660 --> 00:01:28.380
a pre-enrollment selection.

00:01:28.380 --> 00:01:32.680
And there was a pre-enrollment selection bias in some of those CAR-T cell studies for patients

00:01:32.680 --> 00:01:37.720
who could wait through the manufacturing period, especially with cilta-cel, where originally

00:01:37.720 --> 00:01:44.860
the trial didn't allow bridging therapy that patients weren't refractory to.

00:01:44.860 --> 00:01:50.460
And so some of us are, I think now we look at maybe the differences in efficacy between

00:01:50.460 --> 00:01:54.060
CAR-T cells and bispecifics were maybe a little bit inflated.

00:01:54.060 --> 00:01:57.840
And so now we now have these phase 3 studies.

00:01:57.840 --> 00:02:03.340
Where we're looking at CAR-T cells and bispecifics in a very similar line of therapy and a very

00:02:03.340 --> 00:02:05.140
similar patient population.

00:02:05.140 --> 00:02:08.520
And not necessarily compared against each other directly, but maybe in more apples to

00:02:08.520 --> 00:02:13.120
apples comparison than those earlier studies might have been.

00:02:13.120 --> 00:02:15.340
And so these are MAJESTIC-3 and CARTITUDE-4 use.

00:02:15.340 --> 00:02:21.040
So you see CARTITUDE-4 took patients in one to three prior lines of therapy who were lenalidomide

00:02:21.040 --> 00:02:26.140
refractory, randomized them to standard of care or cilta-cel, MAJESTIC-3 did basically

00:02:26.140 --> 00:02:27.140
the same thing.

00:02:27.140 --> 00:02:32.060
They had similar eligibility criteria and an identical standard of care to which these

00:02:32.060 --> 00:02:36.320
were compared.

00:02:36.320 --> 00:02:40.560
So these are the patient populations, just some very kind of summary statistics on them.

00:02:40.560 --> 00:02:45.180
And I think they're overall similar, except for, I know by an hour at the end there, the

00:02:45.180 --> 00:02:50.740
fact that CARTITUDE-4 did enroll more patients who had previously received anti-CD38 antibodies

00:02:50.740 --> 00:02:56.440
where MAJESTIC-3 was an anti-CD38 naive population for the most part.

00:02:56.440 --> 00:02:57.440
So these are the results.

00:02:57.440 --> 00:03:06.580
And of course we're splitting cares between these two very effective therapies in and

00:03:06.580 --> 00:03:08.680
of themselves.

00:03:08.680 --> 00:03:12.940
They're kind of unprecedented results for relapsed multiple myeloma.

00:03:12.940 --> 00:03:18.540
But you see here really dramatic differences between the treatment and control arms in

00:03:18.540 --> 00:03:23.520
favor of cilta-cel and teclistamab.

00:03:23.520 --> 00:03:25.520
And the point I would make is that...

00:03:25.520 --> 00:03:30.040
I won't try to say that teclistamab is better than cilta-cel, but at the very least you have

00:03:30.040 --> 00:03:31.880
to say it's comparable, right?

00:03:31.880 --> 00:03:36.160
And so that initial efficacy difference that we saw from the phase one studies where it

00:03:36.160 --> 00:03:40.000
really looked like CAR-T cells were more potent, it's hard to make that argument here.

00:03:40.000 --> 00:03:41.500
At the very least, these are comparable.

00:03:41.500 --> 00:03:44.400
You could make an argument that teclistamab is better, but at the very least you have

00:03:44.400 --> 00:03:46.040
to say that these are comparable.

00:03:46.040 --> 00:03:50.840
So we shouldn't think of CAR-T cells based on these results as inherently more potent,

00:03:50.840 --> 00:03:53.760
especially in the early relapse setting than by specific antibodies.

00:03:53.760 --> 00:03:54.760
A lot of these studies have shown that in the early relapse settings, these antibodies

00:03:54.760 --> 00:03:55.760
were more potent.

00:03:55.760 --> 00:03:59.060
A lot's been made of the fact that CAR-T4 had some DARA-refractory patients on it.

00:03:59.060 --> 00:04:05.400
But if you look at some subgroup analysis of CAR-T4, it didn't look like the response

00:04:05.400 --> 00:04:09.780
to cilta-cel varied very much between the DARA-tumormab-exposed and unexposed patients.

00:04:09.780 --> 00:04:14.740
And so I don't think we can say that CAR-T4 sort of...

00:04:14.740 --> 00:04:19.280
That you can't compare these populations because of that very, I think, relatively small difference

00:04:19.280 --> 00:04:23.200
in DARA-tumormab exposure between the studies.

00:04:23.200 --> 00:04:24.760
So if we have comparable efficacy...

00:04:24.760 --> 00:04:30.500
Arguably, safety should really drive the decision on which one of these we use in second

00:04:30.500 --> 00:04:32.440
line of therapy.

00:04:32.440 --> 00:04:36.400
And so a cilta-cel has the appeal of being a one-and-done therapy, but of course, that's

00:04:36.400 --> 00:04:39.100
only if you get through it without any major toxicity.

00:04:39.100 --> 00:04:45.020
And we heard Sergio talk earlier about his practice where you have a handful of patients,

00:04:45.020 --> 00:04:48.400
like 6% or something, right, that are dealing with serious complications.

00:04:48.400 --> 00:04:54.760
And you know, you have this litany of individually rare, but collectively not insubstantial toxicities

00:04:54.760 --> 00:04:58.220
that are severe and life-threatening.

00:04:58.220 --> 00:05:02.040
And then at the very least, life-altering or at least making it kind of a chronic disease.

00:05:02.040 --> 00:05:07.240
And so I think we've heard about the different neuropathies on CAR-T4.

00:05:07.240 --> 00:05:09.860
Most of those are resolved, but not all of them.

00:05:09.860 --> 00:05:15.340
The Parkinsonism is very rare, 1%, but 1% still for potentially fatal and serious toxicity

00:05:15.340 --> 00:05:17.800
in second line of myeloma therapy.

00:05:17.800 --> 00:05:23.440
We looked at our patients at Penn, and there's really this list of different immunologic

00:05:23.440 --> 00:05:24.440
complications.

00:05:24.440 --> 00:05:29.520
And in the patients who get those complications, there's a 17% non-relapse mortality in patients

00:05:29.520 --> 00:05:34.460
driven by sepsis from immune suppression that's required to treat them.

00:05:34.460 --> 00:05:36.180
And then second malignancies.

00:05:36.180 --> 00:05:39.940
If you look at kind of the initial publication and follow-up publications, there is an accrual

00:05:39.940 --> 00:05:44.900
of second malignancies that seems more substantial in the Cilta arm than in the standard of care

00:05:44.900 --> 00:05:45.900
arm.

00:05:45.900 --> 00:05:49.160
So again, we're splitting hairs here between very, very good and very, very effective therapies.

00:05:49.160 --> 00:05:53.600
But if we accept that there's comparable efficacy in second line of therapy, it seems like we

00:05:53.600 --> 00:05:54.120
should let safety judge that.

00:05:54.120 --> 00:05:55.020
If we accept that there's comparable efficacy in second line of therapy, it seems like we

00:05:55.020 --> 00:05:56.020
should let safety judge the decision.

00:05:56.020 --> 00:06:05.200
And so a lot of folks are concerned about giving bispecifics before CAR-T cells, and

00:06:05.200 --> 00:06:10.560
I think there's a lot of reason to worry about effect of bispecifics on infection risk

00:06:10.560 --> 00:06:15.780
over time, and then the ability to get CAR-T cells in a future line of therapy.

00:06:15.780 --> 00:06:23.120
However, we don't have to decide, I think if we start patients on following Majestic3

00:06:23.120 --> 00:06:23.800
on Tec or TecDar.

00:06:23.800 --> 00:06:30.800
I think we're going to learn a lot in the time that those patients are on that therapy

00:06:30.800 --> 00:06:34.120
that's going to mitigate some of the problems that we currently think about when giving

00:06:34.120 --> 00:06:36.520
bispecifics before CAR-T cells.

00:06:36.520 --> 00:06:41.320
And I'll mention asphyxiation therapy, it's been mentioned earlier in the talk, or earlier

00:06:41.320 --> 00:06:43.500
in today.

00:06:43.500 --> 00:06:47.680
This is a trial that we've been doing at Penn, taking patients in the relapse setting.

00:06:47.680 --> 00:06:52.720
So median four or five prior lines of therapy and stopping to Clistamab if they have a very

00:06:52.720 --> 00:06:53.480
good partial response.

00:06:53.480 --> 00:06:57.820
After six to nine months of therapy, and you see here that these patients have a median

00:06:57.820 --> 00:07:02.020
progression-free survival after stopping to Clistamab of 20 months.

00:07:02.020 --> 00:07:04.380
And this is in the really heavily relapse setting.

00:07:04.380 --> 00:07:07.640
And those patients who are progressing early on, they're predominantly progressing with

00:07:07.640 --> 00:07:11.140
BCMA negative disease, indicating that those patients would have progressed even if they

00:07:11.140 --> 00:07:12.940
had continued to Clistamab.

00:07:12.940 --> 00:07:16.500
You can imagine kind of porting that to an early relapse setting.

00:07:16.500 --> 00:07:20.000
I think in the future, we're going to be able to shorten the course of therapy.

00:07:20.000 --> 00:07:25.040
And if we shorten the course of therapy, and years later after stopping, patients progress,

00:07:25.040 --> 00:07:27.380
I think they're going to be able to get CAR-T cells just fine.

00:07:27.380 --> 00:07:30.440
I think T cells are going to be fit.

00:07:30.440 --> 00:07:34.840
I think we're going to see less selection for targeted negative disease in that setting.

00:07:34.840 --> 00:07:39.340
And also get some of the benefits of the one and done therapy by shortening the course

00:07:39.340 --> 00:07:43.380
of Bispecific therapy.

00:07:43.380 --> 00:07:48.520
So for a typical patient who starts Tecdara, according to Majestic 3, they're not going

00:07:48.520 --> 00:07:49.680
to likely need another therapy for years.

00:07:49.680 --> 00:07:52.840
And at that point, I think we're going to have learned a lot more.

00:07:52.840 --> 00:07:56.300
We're going to be able to get them CAR-T cell therapy if they need it by limiting the duration

00:07:56.300 --> 00:08:00.300
of bispecifics, and that the CAR-T cell therapy will likely be safer.

00:08:00.300 --> 00:08:03.340
Or at the very least, if you're biting off the risk of CAR-T cell therapy, you're biting

00:08:03.340 --> 00:08:06.600
it off in a later line of therapy where that risk is more justified.

00:08:06.600 --> 00:08:10.520
And then of course, that's not even getting into the question of the accessibility and

00:08:10.520 --> 00:08:14.560
simplicity of bispecifics relative to CAR-T cells.

00:08:14.560 --> 00:08:18.840
So in conclusion, I suspect that Tec3 results will displace much of the early line CAR-T

00:08:18.840 --> 00:08:19.360
cell therapy.

00:08:19.360 --> 00:08:21.640
and at least in my practice, it's already done so.

00:08:22.300 --> 00:08:22.740
Thank you.
